#Text=Cuthbert Burby
#Text=Cuthbert
#Text=Burby
#Text=( died 1607 ) was a London bookseller and publisher of the Elizabethan and early Jacobean eras .
#Text=He is known for publishing a series of significant volumes of English Renaissance drama , including works by William Shakespeare , Robert Greene , John Lyly , and Thomas Nashe .
#Text=Beginnings
#Text=Burby ( " sometimes confused with Cuthbert Burbage , " [ 1 ] though there is no known connection between the two men ) was the son of Edmund Burby , a farmer in Erlsey , Bedfordshire .
#Text=Cuthbert Burby was apprenticed to the stationer William Wright for eight years as of Christmas 1584 , and became a " freeman " ( full member ) of the Stationers Company on 13 January 1592 .
#Text=He did business in London between 1592 and 1607 .

#Text=As his title pages attest , his shops were located 1 ) " under Saint Mildred 's Church in the Poultry , " 2 ) " at the Royal Exchange , " and 3 ) " in Paul 's Churchyard at the sign of the Swan .

#Text=The title page of the R&J Q2 states that that edition was  Newly corrected , augmented , and amended " – which has been interpreted to indicate that Q2 was issued as a deliberate correction and replacement for the defective Q1 , the " bad quarto " printed by John Danter in 1597 .

column1: #Text=The title page of Burby 's Q1 of LLL , the earliest play text to be printed under Shakespeare 's name , also claims that that edition was " Newly corrected and augmented " – which has been taken by some commentators as a possible indication of an earlier " bad quarto " of LLL that has not survived . [ 5 ]
#Text=Burby had subsidiary connections with the Shakespeare canon as well .
#Text=He published Palladis Tamia ( 1598 ) by Francis Meres , which contains an important reference to Shakespeare and a list of Shakespearean works produced up to 1598 .

#Text=Burby also published ( with no attribution of authorship ) the first two quartos of The Taming of a Shrew ( Q1 , 1594 ; Q2 , 1596 ) , the early alternative version of Shakespeare 's The Taming of the Shrew . [ 6 ]

#Text=Also , Burby issued the two early quartos of Edward III ( 1596 , 1599 ) , the one play of the Shakespeare Apocrypha that is most commonly seen as having at least some of Shakespeare 's work in it .
#Text=Other drama
#Text=Burby published a number of other plays , attributed or anonymous , during his career :
#Text=The Cobbler 's Prophecy , Robert Wilson ( 1594 )
#Text=George a Greene , or The Pinner of Wakefield ( 1599 )
#Text=A Knack to Know an Honest Man ( 1596 )
#Text=Mother Bombie , John Lyly ( 1594 , 1598 )
#Text=Orlando Furioso , Robert Greene ( 1594 , 1599 ) .

#Text=Burby 's relationship with the texts of Robert Greene is worth noting ; in addition to Orlando Furioso , Burby issued Greene 's pamphlets The Third and Last Part of Coney-Catching and The Repentance of Robert Greene ( both 1592 ) .
#Text=The play George a Greene has sometimes been attributed to Greene 's pen .
#Text=Burby often worked with the printers John Danter and Simon Stafford , as with many of the texts listed above .
#Text=Other works

#Text=Also in 1594 , Burby published The Second Report of Doctor Faustus , Containing His Appearances , and the Deeds of Wagner – an anonymous prose work that elaborated the story of the magician , and which was written to capitalise on the success of Marlowe 's famous play Doctor Faustus .
#Text=And he published Thomas Lodge 's Wit 's Misery and the World 's Madness in 1596 .
#Text=Burby published other books on a range of subjects .
#Text=He was one of the three publishers who issued Robert Allot 's verse anthology England 's Parnassus in 1600 ( the other two being Nicholas Ling and Thomas Heyes ) .

#Text=He published many religious works , as did all the publishers of his era ; and he issued some of the multi-volume chivalric romances that were the best-sellers of the age , like The Mirror of Knighhood and Champions of Christendom .
#Text=Post mortem
#Text=The exact date of Burby 's death is not known , though it fell between 24 August and 26 September in 1607 .
#Text=In 1609 Burby 's widow assigned his copyrights – mainly of theological works – to the publisher 's former apprentice Nicholas Bourne .
#Text=Bourn had printed no dramatic works in his career , but was a successful publisher of news who worked for many years in partnership with Nathaniel Butter . [ 7 ] [ 8 ]
#Text=The overall quality of Burby 's work as a publisher has been variously evaluated .
#Text=Commentators have complained about the quality of the printing in some of Burby 's texts ; while Burby was not a printer , it can be asserted that he should have employed better craftsmen .

#Text=It has even been argued that the printing in the " bad quarto " of Romeo and Juliet , Danter 's 1597 Q1 , is superior to the printing of the Burby/Creede Q2 , the " good " quarto of 1599 – that Q2 " is on the whole less carefully printed than Q1 .
